{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487444","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487444"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:10:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:10:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"349"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"349","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/349"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.07,0.25,0.54,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"349"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97536"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"349","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/349"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"349"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80136"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5364"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1280"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1300"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16218"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35689"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43791"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44976"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97536","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97536"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for a health check. He enjoys good health with no gastrointestinal symptoms. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His family history includes his father developing bowel cancer at the age of 55 and a maternal aunt who had the same disease at the age of 50. He asks about screening for colorectal cancer.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate advice for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Colonoscopy every 5 years from age 35","Colonoscopy annually from age 40","Colonoscopy every 5 years from age 40","Colonoscopy every 5 years from age 45","Colonoscopy annually from age 50"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a first-degree relative (his father) who developed colorectal cancer at age 55, placing him in the moderate risk group (category 2) for colorectal cancer. The most appropriate recommendation is \u003Cstrong\u003Ecolonoscopy every 5 years from age 45\u003C/strong\u003E, which is 10 years before the age of diagnosis of his first-degree relative. In addition to colonoscopy screening, the patient could be considered for chemoprophylaxis with low-dose aspirin commencing age 45 to further reduce their risk of colorectal cancer, after discussing the benefits and risks with their healthcare provider.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColonoscopy every 5 years from age 35\u003C/strong\u003E is too early and too frequent for this patient\u0027s risk category. While early screening can be beneficial, starting at age 35 is not recommended for moderate risk individuals and could lead to unnecessary procedures and potential complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColonoscopy every 5 years from age 40\u003C/strong\u003E is too early. Although this is 10 years before his aunt\u0027s age at diagnosis, colonoscopy commencement is based on the age of the youngest first-degree relative, not second-degree.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColonoscopy annually \u003C/strong\u003Eis too frequent an interval for colorectal cancer screening. Annual colonoscopy screening may be considered for certain very high-risk populations e.g. hereditary polyposis syndromes, high-risk ulcerative colitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe current colorectal cancer risk categories and screening recommendations based on family history are as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECategory 1 - similar risk as the general population\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAsymptomatic people with no family history of colorectal cancer OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOne 1st-degree relative with CRC \u226560 years\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScreening\u003C/strong\u003E: FOBT should be completed every 2 years from 45 years old as per usual screening protocol. Colonoscopy is generally not recommended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECategory 2 - moderately increased risk\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAsymptomatic people with one 1st-degree relative CRC diagnosed \u0026lt;60 years OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETwo 1st-degree relatives with CRC at any age or one 1st-degree and one or more 2nd-degree relatives diagnosed at any age\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScreening\u003C/strong\u003E: Colonoscopy should be offered 5 yearly starting at \u003Cstrong\u003E10 years younger\u003C/strong\u003E than the earliest diagnosis of CRC in a 1st-degree relative, or age \u003Cstrong\u003E50 \u003C/strong\u003E(whichever is earliest).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECategory 3 - high risk, excluding hereditary cancer syndromes\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAsymptomatic with two 1st-degree and one 2nd-degree relative with colorectal cancer, with at least one diagnosed before 50 years old OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETwo 1st-degree relatives and two or more 2nd-degree relatives diagnosed with CRC at any age OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThree or more 1st-degree relatives with CRC at any age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScreening\u003C/strong\u003E: refer to the familial cancer clinic for genetic assessment before a screening decision is made if Lynch syndrome has not been excluded. If Lynch syndrome is excluded, colonoscopy should be offered every 5 years starting at \u003Cstrong\u003E10 years younger\u003C/strong\u003E than the earliest age of diagnosis of colorectal cancer in a first-degree relative or age \u003Cstrong\u003E40 \u003C/strong\u003Eyears (whichever is earliest)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Patients with one first-degree relative diagnosed with colorectal cancer before the age of 60 are in the moderate risk group and should have 5-yearly colonoscopy commencing at 10 years younger than the age of diagnosis of their first-degree relative"],"references":["RACGP. Guidance for preventative activities in general practice: colorectal cancer. 2024. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/preventive-activities-in-general-practice/cancer/colorectal-cancer","Cancer Council Australia. Clinical practice guidelines for the prevention, early detection and management of colorectal cancer: Risk and screening based on family history. 2024. Available at: https://app.magicapp.org/#/guideline/jz5DdE"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80136"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"349"}},"stemM